    <span class="eyebrow">About</span>
    <h1>Why I built this</h1>
    <p class="thesis">I'm <b>Alan Lacroix</b>. I was born in Mexico City, grew up in Miami, and am now building a business in Mexico. Going back, I realized I understood the country less than I thought. The peso was at 17.5 and I couldn't say whether that was good. The minimum wage had tripled in three years and I couldn't say why. I wanted to answer these questions from facts and come to my own conclusions.</p>
    <p>The data exists. Banxico, INEGI, and Hacienda publish most of it, but it's scattered, and the headlines are sensationalized. I was tired of going to news sites and only reading about cartel violence. The Mexico Brief pulls the first-party data into one place, next to the news that explains it. Every figure carries its source and date.</p>
    <p>I built it for myself. Family and friends started using it, so I'm opening it up.</p>
    <p>I look at Mexico mostly from a US vantage point. I'm interested in its political stability, its economic growth, the trade relationship with the US, and how it's positioned in AI, technology, private equity, and entrepreneurship in the region.</p>
    <p>Hopefully this brings a bit of much-needed transparency and demystification to the world's 13th largest economy, the United States' biggest trading partner, and always a first-knockout-round exit in the World Cup.</p>
